## 1. Purpose

This policy explains how [Business Name] protects its business data by making regular copies (backups) of important information, and how we would recover that information if something went wrong — such as ransomware, accidental deletion, a hardware failure, or a fire.

The goal is simple: if we lose access to our data today, how quickly can we get back to working normally, and what would we lose?

---

## 2. Why This Matters

Consider what would happen if you lost access to everything tomorrow:

- Customer contact details and job history
- Invoices, quotes, and financial records
- Supplier contacts and purchase history
- Email history
- Any documents, certificates, or insurance records stored digitally

Without backups, some or all of this could be gone permanently. With good backups, recovery is frustrating but manageable.

Under GDPR, we also have a responsibility to protect customer data. Losing it through preventable means (no backups, no recovery plan) is a compliance failure, not just a business inconvenience.

---

## 3. Scope

This policy covers:

- All customer data (contact details, job records, quotes, invoices)
- Financial records (accounting data, invoices, bank records)
- Business email
- Documents and files used in day-to-day operations
- Any software configuration that would take significant time to rebuild

This policy applies to:

- [List the systems you use — e.g. Tradify, Xero, Microsoft 365, QuickBooks, shared drives, local computers, etc.]
- [All employees who manage or access business data]

---

## 4. What We Back Up and How

### 4.1 Cloud Software (SaaS Applications)

Most modern business software handles backup automatically. The key is knowing what your provider does — and whether it covers the scenarios you're worried about.

| System | What's at risk | Provider backup | What we do additionally |
|---|---|---|---|
| [e.g. Tradify] | Job records, customer data, photos | [Yes/No — check provider] | [e.g. Monthly export to CSV saved to OneDrive] |
| [e.g. Xero] | Financial records, invoices | [Yes — Xero maintains backups] | [e.g. Quarterly export of accounts data] |
| [e.g. Microsoft 365] | Email, OneDrive files, Teams] | [Yes — but recycle bin has limits] | [e.g. Export critical emails annually] |
| [Any other systems] | | | |

**Important:** Cloud provider backups protect against hardware failures on their side. They may NOT protect you against:
- Accidental deletion (some have short recovery windows — check)
- Ransomware that syncs encrypted files to the cloud
- Account being compromised and data deleted maliciously
- Provider going out of business

Check your key providers' backup and recovery terms. Know the answers to: how long do they keep deleted data? Can you restore a specific file from 30 days ago?

---

### 4.2 Local Files and Documents

If you have important files stored locally on computers (not in cloud storage), these need separate backup arrangements.

**What we back up locally:**
[List any local files that aren't automatically in the cloud — e.g. "Quotes folder on office PC", "Scanned certificates in Documents folder"]

**How we back these up:**
[Choose and describe your approach — examples below]

**Option A — External hard drive:**
> We back up the [folder names] on [computer name] to an external hard drive every [weekly/monthly]. The hard drive is stored [offsite location — e.g. "at James's home" or "in a fireproof safe"] when not in use. [Name] is responsible for running the backup.

**Option B — Automatic cloud sync:**
> All important documents are stored in [OneDrive/Google Drive/Dropbox], which automatically syncs to the cloud. We verify the sync is working on the first Monday of each month.

**Option C — Both:**
> Critical files are in OneDrive (automatic sync) and we also run a monthly backup to an external drive as a second copy.

---

### 4.3 The 3-2-1 Rule (Aim For This)

A useful target for backup coverage:
- **3** copies of important data
- **2** different storage types (e.g. cloud + external drive)
- **1** copy stored offsite (not in the same building as the others)

Not every small business needs this level of redundancy for every file. Apply it to your most critical data — the stuff where losing it would seriously damage the business.

